<HEADLINE>
<P>
ADS ON TEAM UNIFORMS RESCUE SCHOOLS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 There are ads on school team uniforms and ads in high school hallways, and 
even the yellow buses of School District 11 have turned into to roving 
billboards for 7-Up, Burger King and other companies. 
</P>
<P>
 "If we were not so short of money, we wouldn't have to do stuff like this," 
said Tracy Cooper, a spokeswoman for El Paso County's District 11."We'll 
consider anything." 
</P>
<P>
 Amendment 1, passed two years ago, caps local governments' growth, so the 
32,000-student district, the state's fourth largest, had to look for new 
sources of funds, Cooper said. 
</P>
<P>
 Ads have raised about $54,000 since the first one went up in September, 1993. 
That might seem like pocket change for a district with a $133-million budget 
this year, but voters haven't approved a bond issue or new tax for the school 
in 22 years. 
</P>
<P>
 No public outcry has materialized. 
</P>
